      "text": "Aquaculture is the captive rearing and production of fish and other aquatic animal and\nplant species under controlled conditions. Many aquatic species have been cultured,\nespecially fish, crustaceans and molluscs and aquatic plants and algae. Aquaculture\nproduction methods have been developed in various regions of the world, and have thus\nbeen adapted to the specific environmental and climatic conditions in those regions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e9a5998ae43867b7",
      "text": "The four major categories of aquaculture include open water systems (e.g. cages, longlines),\npond culture, flow-through raceways and recirculating aquaculture systems\n(RAS). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7ca7200b9d3108af",
      "text": "In a RAS operation water is reused for the fish after a cleaning\nand a filtering process. Although a RAS is not the cheapest production system owing\nto its higher investment, energy and management costs, it can considerably increase\nproductivity per unit of land and is the most efficient water-saving technology in\nfish farming. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ff5249cf6ef4b6dc",
      "text": "A RAS is the most applicable method for the development of integrated\naquaculture agriculture systems because of the possible use of by-products and the\nhigher water nutrient concentrations for vegetable crop production."
